{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d3bc385-2294-41df-ad1a-8a1501bb1e59","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **Window lifecycle events**. You hook into them via `CreateWindow` or by subclassing `Window`:\n\n```csharp\n// In your App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* equivalent to OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* equivalent to OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* equivalent to OnResume */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n- Lifecycle is now **per-window**, not per-app (supports multi-window).\n- Additional events available: `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Backgrounding`.\n- You can also use platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for finer control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f3b06f7-e2a5-4a1c-adad-9d34244a3aaf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI, specifically about the lifecycle methods OnStart, OnSleep, and OnResume that were overridden in the Application class in Xamarin.Forms.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of overriding those methods directly on the Application class, MAUI uses a cross-platform lifecycle events system through the `Window` class or by subscribing to lifecycle events.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":388,"requestId":"5010:739A4:1BA128E:1EAC63E:69FA90F6"},"id":"a441f242-83e9-4021-9551-440b200880f0","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:53:18.898Z","parentId":"4f469f42-3735-4ea5-9e95-037202fd74c5"}
